The total value of capital importation into Nigeria stood at $16.81 billion in 2018 compared to $12.22 billion capital imported in 2017, the National Bureau of Statistics (NBS) has said. The data for the report, which was supplied by the Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN), verified by NBS, ac-cording to the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN), said the figures represented 37.49 per cent growth year-on-year. The NBS disclosed this in Nigerian Capital Importation for Fourth Quarter and Full Year, 2018 report posted on its website. Meanwhile, the NBS said Nigeria recorded a decline in the total value of capital importation into the country in the fourth quarter, 2018 which stood at $2.14 billion. According to the report, the total capital value represents a decrease of 25.05 per cent compared to third quarter, 2018 and 60.24 per cent decrease compared to the fourth quarter of 2017. Capital Importation can be divided into three main investment types: Foreign Direct Investments (FDIs), Portfolio Investments and Other Investments. The largest amount of capital importation by type was received through Portfolio investments, which accounted for 70.20 per cent ($11.80 billion) of total capital importation. This was followed by Other Investments, which accounted for 22.69 per cent ($3.81 billion) of total capital and FDIs which accounted for 7.11 per cent ($1.19 billion) of total capital imported in 2018. By sector, Capital importation by shares, which is closely related to Equity in-vestment (FDI and Portfolio Investment) dominated 2018 reaching $10,425.18 of the total capital Importation in 2018. The United Kingdom emerged as the top source of capital investment in Nigeria the year under review with $6.01billion investment, stressing that his accounted for 35.74 per cent of the total capital inflow in 2018. The second on the list of top 10 was the US, with capital investment of $3.57 billion. This was followed by the South Africa with the capital investment of $1.15 billion in the year under review. Foreign investments in the telecommunications sector rose marginally by 2.6 per cent in the third quarter of this year. Total investment inflow to the sector between June and September stood at $11.42 million according to latest statics released by the National Bureau of Statistics (NBS). In the previous quarter,… In "Business" Banks attract $543.4m FDI   The total capital imported to Nigeria stood at $12.228 billion in 2017, a data of the National Bureau of Statistics (NBS) obtained yesterday indicated. The figure represents an increase of $7.104 billion or 138.7 per cent from the figure recorded in 2016 while capital inflows… In "News" India remains Nigeria’s biggest trade partner   The total investments inflow into Nigeria in the first quarter of 2017 nosedived to 908.27 million, the report of the National Bureau of Statistics (NBS) has shown. The figure represents a huge decline of $640.61 million or 41.36 per cent, compared to $1.55… In "News"